tsd:news_padi_web_92442 a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:92442" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "fe767baab1f9ce3d1c717a054c5dcb45fb834f57b546c53b7a754e72a2a2c88e" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Minnesota loses another flock to avian flu" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Minnesota loses another flock to avian flu

Minnesota loses another flock to avian flu

The USDA Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service confirmed another commercial poultry flock in Minnesota has tested positive for highly pathogenic avian influenza this month, bringing the tally to four commercial flocks so far in May.

APHIS said the most recent detection was confirmed in Becker County on May 20 and affected a commercial breeder operation.

Four flocks in May
Becker County has been the site of all four of the state's May detections, and the county lost a reported 66,400 head of commercial poultry to HPAI during the month.

Two of the other infected operations in Becker County were also described as commercial breeder operations, while the fourth was listed as commercial turkey breeder replacement hens.

66,400 birds lost
Before this cluster in Becker County, the most recent Minnesota confirmation was reported in mid-April in a commercial meat turkey flock in Big Stone County.

Outside Minnesota, the only other state with a confirmed commercial poultry case so far in May is Indiana, according to APHIS reporting.

Becker County cluster
APHIS described the May 20 affected site as a commercial breeder operation that housed 4,300 birds.

Calls to depopulate or quarantine affected flocks and to apply biosecurity measures are standard following confirmations, and APHIS is the reporting agency for those actions.

4,300 birds in flock
State and federal officials continue to track detections and publish case information as investigations proceed.

APHIS maintains case listings and updates as investigations confirm cases and determine the scope of affected operations.

Tracking cases
Producers and industry stakeholders looking for an interactive view of recent commercial-poultry HPAI detections across North America can consult the map available at WATTPoultry.com, which tracks confirmed cases in the United States, Mexico and Canada.

The APHIS case reports and the WATTPoultry map currently show Minnesota’s May cluster concentrated in Becker County and a separate commercial confirmation in Indiana.

Photo - img.wattagnet.com""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-23"^^xsd:date ;
