tsd:news_padi_web_bird_flu_returns_friesland_flevoland_forcing_culling_135000_birds a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:bird-flu-returns-friesland-flevoland-forcing-culling-135000-birds" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "699e9b937a55c33d79eaea84e76d190612da44ec0232877561eb9e0ff81b3227" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Bird flu returns in Friesland and Flevoland, forcing culling of over 135,000 birds" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Bird flu returns in Friesland and Flevoland, forcing culling of over 135,000 birds

Bird flu returns in Friesland and Flevoland, forcing culling of over 135,000 birds

Bird flu has resurfaced in the Netherlands, with outbreaks confirmed at a poultry farm in Marrum, in the province of Friesland, and earlier at a farm in Biddinghuizen, the government reports.

In total, more than 135,000 birds have been culled: about 55,000 chickens in Biddinghuizen and more than 80,000 meat chicks in Marrum.

The latest outbreak in Marrum, located in North Friesland, involves a meat chicken farm where authorities confirmed avian influenza.

The 80,000 chicks on the property are being destroyed as part of containment measures.

The new case is notable because highly contagious bird flu typically spreads mainly in the autumn and winter months, when large numbers of wild birds are migrating through the region.

On April 21, Dutch authorities lifted the national housing and shielding requirement for poultry in most of the country, concluding that the highest risk period had passed.

That measure now remains in force only in the Gelderse Vallei, an area including the municipalities of Barneveld and Lunteren, where poultry farming is heavily concentrated.

Despite that easing of restrictions, two new infections have now been confirmed.

Last week, 55,000 chickens were culled at a poultry farm in Biddinghuizen in Flevoland.

The most recent case followed in Marrum, according to Omrop Fryslân.

The outbreaks have prompted additional containment measures in Friesland.

Within a three-kilometer radius of the infected farm in Marrum, there is one other commercial poultry operation.

Within a ten-kilometer zone, there are 11 poultry farms.

Authorities have imposed a transport ban in this area covering birds, poultry manure, and eggs.

The Dutch Food and Consumer Product Safety Authority, known as NVWA, is conducting tracing investigations into what it describes as “risky contacts,” examining whether poultry or poultry products were transported to or from the Marrum farm in the period before the infection was detected.""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-25"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:50:43.062556+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://nltimes.nl/2026/05/25/bird-flu-returns-friesland-flevoland-forcing-culling-135000-birds"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_cac_tinh_thanh_pho_thuc_hien_ke_hoach_quoc_gia_phong_chong_dich_benh_cho_dong_vat_nuoi_giai_doan_2026_2030 a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:cac-tinh-thanh-pho-thuc-hien-ke-hoach-quoc-gia-phong-chong-dich-benh-cho-dong-vat-nuoi-giai-doan-2026-2030" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "ccc9b72d365f2606c210ceade804e5d62575b2f35f21e52eca4613a10edac6df" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Provinces and cities are implementing the National Plan for the Prevention and Control of Animal Diseases for the period 2026-2030." ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Provinces and cities are implementing the National Plan for the Prevention and Control of Animal Diseases for the period 2026-2030.

Provinces and cities are implementing the National Plan for the Prevention and Control of Animal Diseases for the period 2026-2030.

Inspection Team No 2 of the Department of Agriculture and Environment of Hanoi conducted a surprise inspection of the origin and sources of pork and chicken meat at the stalls of the Thuong Thanh Market (Vinh Hung District).

Photo: --------- The document states:

In order to implement the National Plan for the Prevention and Control of Avian Influenza, Foot-and-Mouth and African Swine Fever 2026-2030 (hereinafter referred to as the National Plan), issued by Decree No 779/QD-TTg dated May 2, 2026 by the Prime Minister, in order to ensure the timely, coherent and effective implementation of the National Plan, the Ministry of Agriculture and Environment requests the chairmen of the people's committees of provinces and cities To entrust the departments of agriculture and environment and specialized departments with the task of taking the lead, coordinating with the relevant units and people's committees at the commune level to formulate and submit the Plan for approval to the competent authorities, and to allocate funds from the local budget in accordance with the law, and to mobilize other legal resources in accordance with the epidemiological situation, the scale of livestock production and the capacity to implement the balanced budget of the settlement.

Submit local plans to the Ministry of Agriculture and Environment (through the Department of Animal Production and Veterinary Medicine) by 5 June 2026 for drafting, monitoring, guidance and coordinated implementation.

The Ministry of Agriculture and Environment has also asked the local authorities to organize vaccination against avian influenza, foot-and-mouth disease and African swine fever in accordance with the law, the National Plan, the guidelines of specialized agencies and the actual situation in the region, while ensuring that the vaccination rate of livestock meets the targets of the National Plan.

In the event of an outbreak, vaccination must be urgently organized to contain the outbreak, eliminate the threat and identify high-risk areas, as directed by specialized agencies.

Veterinarians administer foot-and-mouth disease vaccine (type OA) to buffalo and cattle in Thuan An commune.

Photo: ---------.

Local authorities need to step up advocacy to raise awareness and accountability among pastoralists and the public regarding disease reporting, vaccination, biosecurity in animal husbandry, and the handling of sick and dead animals; preventing the concealment of disease outbreaks, the sale of sick animals, the dumping of dead animal carcasses into the environment, or any activity that contributes to the spread of disease; strengthening the inspection, management and organization of biosafety and disease protection in animal production, taking into account the species of animals, the scale of animal production, agricultural methods and the specific conditions of each locality; Establishing risk-based surveillance, combining passive, active and post-vaccination surveillance on livestock farms, markets, collection points, slaughterhouses, transport routes, border areas, outbreak areas and areas designated as disease-free zones; instructing local authorities to strengthen the inspection and control of the transport, trade and slaughter of animals and animal products; Prevent, detect and strictly suppress the transport and trade of animals and animal products of unknown origin that are subject to quarantine but have not yet been quarantined in accordance with regulations, as well as those that do not meet the requirements of veterinary hygiene and disease safety, especially in places with borders, border points, open routes, trails, ports and large commercial areas.

Local authorities should review and select suitable areas, facilities and livestock supply chains in advance to establish disease-free zones, in accordance with Vietnamese law, World Organisation for Animal Health recommendations, and the requirements of importing countries and markets.

Source: https://hanoimoi.vn/cac-tinh-thanh-pho-thuc-hien-ke-hoach-quoc-gia-phong-chong-dich-benh-cho-dong-vat-nuoi-giai-doan-2026-2030-750907.html""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-22"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:54:00.342833+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.vietnam.vn/ru/cac-tinh-thanh-pho-thuc-hien-ke-hoach-quoc-gia-phong-chong-dich-benh-cho-dong-vat-nuoi-giai-doan-2026-2030"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_cdc_enhanced_ebola_airport_screening_html a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:cdc-enhanced-ebola-airport-screening.html" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "6574582aa485f20d470f5e054082ebbb74a02ff657e315be214f24a86ca978d9" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "CDC: Enhanced Ebola Airport Screening Begins at Washington-Dulles International Airport" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# CDC: Enhanced Ebola Airport Screening Begins at Washington-Dulles International Airport

CDC: Enhanced Ebola Airport Screening Begins at Washington-Dulles International Airport

#19,171As we discussed 3 days ago in CDC Statement on the Use of Public Health Travel Restrictions to Prevent the Introduction of Ebola Disease into the United States, we possess no technology that permits us to reliably screen presymptomatic travelers entering the United States for infectious diseases.

Temperature screening and health questionnaires can help identify some infected individuals - but with incubation periods that can range from days to weeks - only a small percentage of cases will likely be detected.

There are obvious advantages to identifying (and isolating) those already showing signs of illness, as they are most likely to be infectious.

But once a virus becomes sufficiently transmissible among humans, the best we can hope for is to slow the spread (see Why Airport Screening Can’t Stop MERS, Ebola or Avian Flu).Different diseases spread at different rates, and luckily Ebola (like Hantavirus) requires far closer, and more prolonged, contact than highly contagious pathogens like measles or influenza.

That doesn't render them incapable of international spread, but neither have shown the ability to spread like a classic pandemic virus (with the caveat that viral evolution means that whatever we say today may not necessarily hold true tomorrow).

Yesterday the CDC announced plans to redirect returning American travelers who have recently (within 21 days) visited the DRC, Uganda, or South Sudan to Washington Dulles International Airport, where they will be screened for potential Ebola exposure.

Those who are asymptomatic will be provided health information - and told what to do if symptoms should later appear - then allowed to proceed to their final destinations.

Those who are symptomatic will be evaluated by a CDC health officer.

Should conditions warrant, there is always the option of adjusting these screening protocols.

The CDC's full statement follows:Enhanced Ebola Airport Screening Begins at Washington-Dulles International AirportStatementFor immediate release: May 21, 2026CDC Media Relations(404) 639-3286On May 18, 2026, the CDC issued an Order suspending entry to the United States of foreign nationals who were in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), Uganda, or South Sudan within 21 days before arrival.

U.S. citizens, U.S. nationals, and lawful permanent residents who were in these countries within 21 days are permitted to enter the United States.

The Department of Homeland Security (DHS) posted a Federal Register notice, available here, that outlines the redirection of these affected travelers to Washington-Dulles International Airport (IAD) beginning 11:59 p.m.

May 20, 2026, for enhanced public health screening.

CDC will conduct the enhanced public health entry screenings for these travelers and confirm their contact information for public health follow-up if recommended.

Travelers that have been in the DRC, Uganda, and South Sudan in the 21 days before their flight, and are scheduled to travel to the United States, while screening is taking place will be contacted by their airline to rebook travel to IAD.To date, no suspected, probable, or confirmed cases of Ebola have been reported in the United States, and the risk of Ebola domestically is low.

However, public health entry screening is part of a layered approach that, when used with other public health measures already in place to detect symptomatic arriving travelers, can slow and reduce the spread of disease into the United States.

How Public Health Entry Screening WorksTravelers who were in DRC, Uganda, or South Sudan in the 21 days before arriving to the United States will be escorted to an area of the airport set aside for screening.

--------- will respond to a brief questionnaire that asks about their travel history and symptoms, and collects information so the --------- can be contacted, if needed.

CDC staff will observe these --------- for signs of illness and take ---------' temperatures using non-contact thermometers (thermometers that do not touch the skin).Travelers who do not have symptoms, but have been in DRC, Uganda, or South Sudan in the past 21 days will be given information on monitoring their health and actions to take if symptoms later appear.

These --------- will continue to their final destinations.

Traveler contact information will be shared with state and local health departments for additional follow-up and support.

If a traveler has a fever or other symptoms, the -------- will be evaluated by a CDC public health officer.

CDC partners with state and local public health authorities and designated hospitals within those states to work quickly to identify and take appropriate public health actions for persons who present with symptoms of illness in the community.

Working together, U.S. federal, state, and local authorities are ready to manage --------- who become ill after they reach their destinations.

If a suspect case is identified, CDC will work with state/local health departments to conduct routine contact investigations to notify passengers.

CDC is prepared to provide additional resources in response to this Ebola outbreak in DRC and Uganda.

The latest information on this outbreak is available here.""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-22"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:53:50.211719+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://afludiary.blogspot.com/2026/05/cdc-enhanced-ebola-airport-screening.html"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_chu_ky_dai_dich_6_nam_lan_dang_viral_mang_xa_hoi_chuyen_gia_bac_bo a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:chu-ky-dai-dich-6-nam-lan-dang-viral-mang-xa-hoi-chuyen-gia-bac-bo" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "a31027fcaf5a0fa28741c6423654f0e178beef4f58643506bcabd1fd5a2b50a8" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "The \"six-year cycle of pandemics\" is gaining popularity on social networks, but experts refute it." ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# The "six-year cycle of pandemics" is gaining popularity on social networks, but experts refute it.

The "six-year cycle of pandemics" is gaining popularity on social networks, but experts refute it.

Epidemiologists deny rumours of a "secret cycle of pandemics" in the world – Photo: AFP In Indonesia, a video is circulating on social media claiming that viral outbreaks or pandemics occur in the world every six years, and even implying that these outbreaks were "deliberately planned".

However, epidemiologists argue that there is no scientific evidence to support this hypothesis.

Accordingly, a video posted on Instagram listed a number of major epidemics, such as SARS in 2002, H1N1 flu in 2009, Ebola, COVID-19 and hantavirus, to create the illusion of a fixed "pandemic cycle".

However, epidemiologist Dickie Budiman of Griffith University said that the history of outbreaks shows that the intervals between epidemics vary greatly and do not obey the six-year rule.

As examples, he cited SARS (2002), H1N1 influenza (2009), Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS) (2012) and COVID-19 (2019).

In addition, Ebola, Zika, avian influenza and hantavirus viruses have appeared at different times.

According to Budiman, the deliberate timing of certain time frames while ignoring other outbreaks created the illusion of a "secret pattern."

He stressed that the Ebola virus was actually discovered in the 1970s, while the Hunt virus was known from the 1950s to the 1970s and is not a recent phenomenon.

The expert said that scientists estimate that there are approximately 1.6 million types of viruses in nature, and about 800,000 of them are capable of causing diseases in humans.

However, mankind has thoroughly studied only a very small part of them.

Experts also warn that people often tend to look for patterns in random events — a phenomenon known as apophenia, that is, seeing connections even when there's no clear cause-and-effect relationship.

Scientists also advise the public to be cautious about information about the pandemic spread on social media, as conspiracy theories related to the pandemic can easily cause panic and distort scientific understanding.

According to historical documents published on the scientific platform ScienceDirect, infectious diseases have existed throughout human history, from the Athenian plague of 430 BC to the Plague of Justinian in 541 and many major outbreaks in the modern era.

Experts say that instead of believing in "pandemic cycles", it is much more important to strengthen epidemiological surveillance, virus research and build global health capacity to reduce the risk of future outbreaks.

Let's get back to the topic.

VNA Source: https://tuoitre.vn/chu-ky-dai-dich-6-nam-lan-dang-viral-mang-xa-hoi-chuyen-gia-bac-bo-20260525172732928.htm""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-25"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:51:04.337287+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.vietnam.vn/ru/chu-ky-dai-dich-6-nam-lan-dang-viral-mang-xa-hoi-chuyen-gia-bac-bo"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_comment_les_nouveaux_chapitres_revises_de_lomsa_assurent_un_meilleur_controle_de_linfluenza_aviaire a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:comment-les-nouveaux-chapitres-revises-de-lomsa-assurent-un-meilleur-controle-de-linfluenza-aviaire" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "482e0e909dbd86eb27ec8fb6b66e4ad0d809978b556dbf8d53910786a7f56ac8" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "How the new revised WOAH chapters ensure better control of avian influenza" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# How the new revised WOAH chapters ensure better control of avian influenza

How the new revised WOAH chapters ensure better control of avian influenza

The 93rd General Session of the World Organisation for Animal Health (WOAH) marked the revision of the WOAH Trade Standard as well as the creation of a brand new resolution on biosafety. This decision was prompted by a request by WOAH Me

bers to include biosafety information in the standards. Like all the other standards developed by the WOAH for implementation b

its Members, those that dominated the agenda this year are set to have a positive impact on animal health and welfare around the world. Among the areas where they bring widespread benefits, the landscape of live poultry markets, wher

infectious diseases such as avian influenza can spread, stands out as a particularly vulnerable yet central space. 
Understanding the issue through the value chain 
Live poultry markets have traditionally played a key role in Southeast Asia and West Africa. In some countries, they form the backbone of cities that depend on food-based trade and tourism. In many of these countries, live poultry markets ensure food secur

ty by providing access to affordable fresh produce and provide a stable source of income for the many vendors who animate this v

brant community space. However, infectious animal diseases such as avian influenza have put these environments under great pressure, as they provide a breeding ground for the emergence and spread of dangerous pathogens. When a zoonotic disease emerges, outbreaks impact p

oultry trade and cause a loss of consumer confidence. Wet markets where live animals are sold and handled are often associated with the transmission of zoonotic diseases, as they can facilitate the movement of live anima

s that may carry pathogens. Interspecies mixing in wet markets further complicates the situation, posing significant risks to health and the environment.

Too often, veterinary public health interventions to curb the spread of the virus have focused on controlling the disease strictly within the markets themselves. Among the measures adopted were a ban on overnight bird storage in markets,

the introduction of days of sanitary closure, and the separation of bird species in markets. As a result of the COVID-19 pandemic, for example, severa

l countries have temporarily closed their wet markets, disrupting trade flows and critical food supply chains. But this solution proved to be neither sustainable nor viable in the long term. It has led t

unintended consequences, such as the emergence of unregulated black markets for animal products and the attribution of the pandemic to these cultural practices. The stigma now associated with "wet markets" has bec

me strongly negative. Conversely, the data show that the control of avian influenza for pandemic prevention purposes must begin before poultry reaches wet markets. Indeed, measures targeting only live poultry marke

s are unlikely to effectively reduce the exposure of traders and buy

rs to the risk of avian influenza if they are not accompanied by appropriate interventions throughout the supply chain. Pandemic prevention strategies should therefore target chicken f

rmers and transporters in countries where the virus is endemic, in order to reduce the number of infected poultry introduced into markets. 
Preparing for the future of poultry markets 
Several studies have identified the main risks associated with these environments. Markets selling

live animals pose the greatest risks to human health and biodiversity due to their pathogen load, especially those involving wild animals, which are closely linked to emerging infectious diseases. Combined factors, such as the presence of live animals, including those at high risk of disease, market s

ze, and cleanliness and hygiene practices, can contribute to the emergence of diseases. 
Given the complex nature of infectious risks, policymakers should not focus solely on markets when seeking to mitigate future outbreaks. Targeted, science-based and risk-based interventions, applied upstream in the supply chain as well as in cross-border bird mov

ments, can make markets avi""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-22"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:53:11.942454+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.woah.org/fr/article/comment-les-nouveaux-chapitres-revises-de-lomsa-assurent-un-meilleur-controle-de-linfluenza-aviaire/"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_controale_in_gospodarii_infractiunea_sanctionata_cu_1_200_de_lei a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:controale-in-gospodarii-infractiunea-sanctionata-cu-1-200-de-lei" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "f6913eaa57e1700414e3db0ebfee74fb1efb223544218cdb8b274bd6cbd55085" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Household controls! The crime sanctioned with 1,200 lei!" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Household controls! The crime sanctioned with 1,200 lei!

Household controls!

The crime sanctioned with 1,200 lei!

------------ – Agrointelligence
May 22, 2026 11:13

DSVSA controls in households

Fines of 3,600 lei and warnings after controls in livestock farms.

In a single week, the official veterinarians from the DSVSA Satu Mare – Official Control Service for Animal Health and Welfare carried out a number of 79 controls in professional and non-professional farms, markets, veterinary sanitary offices, veterinary pharmacies.

Following the recent controls carried out by DSVSA Satu Mare, 5 contravention sanctions were applied, 3 contravention fines in the total amount of – 3,600 lei, as follows: a contravention fine in the amount of 1,200 lei for a non-professional farm in Eriu Sâncrai, a contravention fine in the amount of 1,200 lei for a non-professional farm in Unimăt,  a contravention fine in the amount of 1,200 lei for a non-professional farm in Ghirișa locality and two warnings in two non-farm farms in Căpleni and Tiream, for the sale or alienation of animals in any way, without the documents provided by the veterinary sanitary legislation in force, according to a press release.

Read also: ---------------, president of ANSVSA, message on the Day of the Veterinarian: "Veterinary medicine represents a noble vocation, unceasingly dedicated to the common good"
Controls on livestock farms
Veterinarians, on alert for the "control" of possible outbreaks of serious diseases

According to the data, in the European Union, Avian Influenza evolves – in primary or secondary outbreaks, both in poultry farms and in the wild area in: Belgium, Czech Republic, Germany, Poland, Denmark, France and Norway.

In the same period, it evolves in the E.U. – African Swine Fever, in outbreaks in: Poland, Romania, Lithuania, Latvia, Germany, Croatia, Spain, Italy, Slovakia, Moldova, Estonia, Bosnia and Herzegovina and Hungary.

In Satu Mare County, there are veterinary sanitary restrictions, due to the outbreaks of African Swine Fever in Amati and Turț localities.

DSVSA Satu Mare, has started the program of inspection actions in animal farms in the county.

These actions aim to carry out surveillance to identify animals with clinical signs of transmissible diseases in cattle, sheep, goats and pigs, existing in non-professional households.

The authorized veterinarians will evaluate the animals existing on each holding.

Animal owners have the obligation to allow access to the concessionaire veterinarians on their own farms and to ensure the containment of the kept animals, for a good and correct evaluation.

Read also:

Sheepdogs who had smallpox on farms were left without animals, and without compensation!

Sheep and goat pox in two counties
The appearance of outbreaks of sheep and goat pox in counties in Romania – Bistrita Nasaud and Mureș – obliges DSVSA Satu Mare to warn all breeders of these species in the county about the special danger posed by the appearance and evolution of this disease in livestock, the institution also notes.

Sheep and goat pox is a highly contagious viral disease caused by a virus of the Poxviridae family (genus Capripoxvirus), which affects small ruminants, causing skin lesions, fever and high mortality, especially in lambs (up to 50–70%).

Although it is not transmissible to humans, the disease causes major economic losses.

The disease is manifested by a series of specific clinical symptoms, easily recognizable by farmers:
– Skin lesions, especially around the muzzle, nose, ears, eyelids, abdomen, legs and genitals;
– High fever (40-42°C) in the first days after infection;
– Decreased appetite and weight loss;
– Lethargy and apathy;
– Excessive lacrimation and nasal secretions, sometimes purulent;
– Inflammation of the lymph nodes;
– Lesions on the oral, nasal and ocular mucous membranes, which can cause breathing and feeding difficulties.""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-22"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:53:52.266646+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://agrointel.ro/351220/controale-in-gospodarii-infractiunea-sanctionata-cu-1-200-de-lei"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_dien_bien_khan_truong_trien_khai_cac_bien_phap_phong_chong_cum_gia_cam_a_h5n1 a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:dien-bien-khan-truong-trien-khai-cac-bien-phap-phong-chong-cum-gia-cam-a-h5n1" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "875e725cd3d59bcd7c4fe36385c27ee08c5c6597d2c69081f0a4c63ced035d10" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Dien Bien: Urgent implementation of avian influenza A (H5N1) prevention and control measures" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Dien Bien: Urgent implementation of avian influenza A (H5N1) prevention and control measures

Dien Bien:

rgent implementation of avian influenza A (H5N1) prevention and control measures

Following t

he discovery of duck samples positive for influenza A (H5N1) virus in Thanh Yen commune, Dien Bien province, analyses were carried out by the Central Centre for Veterinary Diagnosis and Analysis I. The samples, from Noong Luong village, T

anh Yen commune, Dien Bien province, tested positive for the virus, a strain that can infect humans. Dien Bien province is stepping up efforts to raise awareness about the prevent

on and control of avian influenza A (H5N1). Faced with the risk of widespread epidemic and spread of the disease, the provincial People's Com

ittee issued official document No. 4223/UBND-KGVX on May 25, asking units and localities to focus on the decisive implementation of disease prevention a

n

d control measures. The People's Committee of Dien Bien province has instructed the Department of Health to coordinate with relevant units to compile a list

of people who have been in close contact with sick or suspected sick poultry, in order to place them under health surveillance for 14 days. At the same time, they must prepare sufficient stocks of medicines, supplies, equipment and isolation areas, and be ready to receive and treat suspected cases of avian influenza

A(H5N1). Community and hospital surveillance is strengthened in order to detect suspected cases early. The Department of Agriculture and Environment is coordinating with local authorities to contain and urgently manage out

reaks, cull sick or suspected diseased poultry, and arrange sanitation, disinfection and sterilization of

ffected areas and their surroundings. It also strengthens disease surveillance in poultry farms, promotes vaccination, and strictly controls the transport, trade, and slaughter of poultry in the region. Source: https://www.qdnd.vn/y-te/tin-tuc/dien-bien-khan-truong-trien-khai-cac-bien-phap-phong-chong-cum-gia-cam-a-h5n1-1041424""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-27"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:49:46.095394+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.vietnam.vn/fr/dien-bien-khan-truong-trien-khai-cac-bien-phap-phong-chong-cum-gia-cam-a-h5n1"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_dien_bien_tieu_huy_5000_con_gia_cam_do_cum_ah5n1_1709276_ldo a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:dien-bien-tieu-huy-5000-con-gia-cam-do-cum-ah5n1-1709276.ldo" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "30510670fef2b419a0406108230d23d44df0c346f4ea87be62be0b16a7216498" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Điện Biên destroys 5,000 poultry due to influenza A/H5N1" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Điện Biên destroys 5,000 poultry due to influenza A/H5N1

Điện Biên destroys 5,000 poultry due to influenza A/H5N1

Functional forces count and destroy flocks of ducks due to influenza A/H5N1 in Thanh Yên commune, Điện Bien province. Photo: Thanh Yen communeOn May 27, l

aders of the People's Committee of Thanh Yen commune, Điện Bien province, said that from May 8 to 22, 2 outbreaks of avian

influenza A/H5N1 appeared in the commune. The first outbreak occurred in the breeding home of ---

-------, a resident of Noong Luong village. After being detected on 8 May, veterinary services collected samples and tes

ed positive for influenza A/H5N1 on 14 May. The entire duck herd, consisting of 1,500 head with a total weight of 1,896 kg, had to be destroyed. On 17 May, a second

outbreak was discovered in the home of ----------, resident in the village of Viet Yen. Test results on May 2

2 were positive for influenza A/H5N1. The authorities organized the destruction of a flock of chickens and duck

of 3,500 heads, for a total weight of 2,612 kg. In order to control t

e epidemic, local authorities have temporarily suspended the purchase, sale, transport and slaughter of poultry and poultry produ

cts in the epidemic area (Noong Luong village, Viet Yen village). The functional forces also sprayed disinfectant around the two outbreaks.""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-27"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:49:29.924940+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://fr.laodong.vn/xa-hoi/dien-bien-tieu-huy-5000-con-gia-cam-do-cum-ah5n1-1709276.ldo"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_dutch_government_moves_towards_mandatory_avian_influenza_vaccination a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:dutch-government-moves-towards-mandatory-avian-influenza-vaccination" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "9e35e8ae24e56a55e7e7ee05ecb4fd6db923cab4c38ea2f987c0792839349121" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Dutch government moves towards mandatory avian influenza vaccination" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Dutch government moves towards mandatory avian influenza vaccination

Dutch government moves towards mandatory avian influenza vaccinationThe government is working together with the poultry sector on a plan to make vaccination against avian influenza mandatory for laying hen farms.

Image created with the help of AI.The Dutch government is working on a plan to make avian influenza vaccination compulsory for all laying hen farms in the country.

Trade barriers remain a major concern.

The government is working together with the poultry sector on a plan to make vaccination against avian influenza mandatory for laying hen farms.

This year, 45 poultry farms have been infected with bird flu.

As a result, almost 2.3 million animals have been culled to prevent the spread of the virus.

“Avian influenza can be highly disruptive for animals, businesses and society,” said the responsible State Secretary for Agriculture, -------------.

“Together with the poultry sector, we are therefore taking a new step towards tackling the virus more effectively.

By focusing on measures such as vaccination, we can begin to reduce avian influenza in a structural way.

In doing so, we are pursuing an internationally accepted approach so that it does not come at the expense of our trade.”No

trade barriersWork on vaccination against the virus has been ongoing for some time.

A field trial has shown that vaccinated animals significantly reduce the risk of a large-scale avian influenza outbreak.

Infections can also still be detected quickly through the mandatory European monitoring programme.

In addition, the first vaccination pilot is progressing well.

“The table eggs from vaccinated hens have been sold on the Dutch market and, so far, no trade barriers have arisen,” according to the Ministry of Agriculture.

In a letter to Parliament, ------ wrote that trading partners are highly appreciative of the transparent way in which the Netherlands has organised and communicated the entire pilot programme.

“The poultry sector has made a constructive contribution to this,” ------ stated.

The ----- will continue until the end of December this year.

Trade barriers remain a major concern regarding the use of vaccination.

For that reason, vaccination is being introduced step by step.

International cooperation is underway to secure acceptance of products from vaccinated poultry.

The Netherlands has taken the initiative to establish an international working group with the US, Canada, France, the UK, the European Commission and the World Organisation for Animal Health.

Plan for mandatory vaccination ------ will spend the coming months working with the poultry sector on an action plan for mandatory vaccination of laying hens against avian influenza.

The action plan is expected to be completed by the end of this year.

However, the poultry sector has set a number of conditions for introducing a vaccination programme.

These are focused on the international acceptance of products from vaccinated poultry.

In addition, the poultry sector is calling for a feasible and affordable surveillance programme.

“The export value of products such as table eggs amounts to around €700 million.

It is therefore of great importance that trade in poultry and poultry products is not harmed.

A careful approach and a proper assessment of the impact on the sector are essential,” ------ wrote in his letter to Parliament.

Flu jab for poultry farmersAlthough the risk of avian influenza transmission to humans is still considered very low, the government is nevertheless taking precautionary measures.

People considered most at risk of infection – including poultry farmers, ------------- and animal ambulance staff – will be offered the opportunity to receive the seasonal influenza vaccination, commonly known as the flu jab, from the next flu season onwards.

This vaccination is not directly intended to reduce the likelihood of people becoming infected with avian influenza.

The primary aim is to prevent any bird flu viruses they may encounter from mixing with human influenza strains.

Pig farmers who may come into contact with swine flu viruses will also be offered the flu jab in order to prevent animal influenza viruses from combining with human strains.

According to public health experts, vaccinating people specifically against bird flu currently offers little added value.

Fewer farms in high-risk areasThe intensified action plan for tackling avian influenza and reducing the risks of zoonotic diseases also examined structural measures to reduce the number of poultry farms in poultry-dense and water-rich areas.

An impact assessment is currently underway into the consequences for public and animal health, as well as for the poultry sector.

The results are expected before the summer.

“These are far-reaching measures that require a solid evidence base and new legal powers.

The guiding principle is that the measures must be appropriate, necessary and proportionate,” ------ said.

Join 31,000+ subscribers Subscribe to our newsletter to stay updated about all the need-to-know content in the poultry sector, three times a week.

"*" indicates required fields""" ;
