tsd:news_padi_web_la_grippe_aviaire_detectee_chez_un_ours_polaire_dans_larctique a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:la-grippe-aviaire-detectee-chez-un-ours-polaire-dans-larctique" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "385f6e3933a932dea70f6757105801c5328b8382b857dc29143ec78879b0496b" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Avian Influenza Detected in Arctic Polar Bear" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Avian Influenza Detected in Arctic Polar Bear

Avian Influenza Detected in Arctic Polar Bear

Avian influenza detected in polar bears. This respiratory path

logy of avian origin crossed biological barriers for the first time in European Arctic ecosystems when its fatal presence was confirmed in a large terrestrial predator.

Necropsies performed on brain tissue support the theory th

at the viral infection was the direct trigger for his death. This scenario repeats contagion patterns already seen in Alaskan wildlife, sounding the al

rm about the vulnerability of populations confined to the pole.
Norwegian authorities announced on Tuesday that bird flu had been detected for the first time

in Europe in a polar bear in the Arctic region of Svalbard. 
Avian flu detected in a polar bear caused its death
The H5N5 variant of the virus was detected in samples taken from a male bear about a year old and a walrus found dead in mid-May in the frozen archipelago, about 1,000 km from the North Pole, according to the Norwegian Veterinary Institute. 

"The findings are part of a trend in which more and more highly pathogenic avian influenza viruses are being detected in mammals in Europe," ------------------, coordinator of avian influenza at the Veterinary Institute, said in a statement.
Avian influenza has been detected in polar bears and Norwegian authorities say that: "At the same time, in recent years, the virus has spread to new regions, including the Arctic, where it can have consequences for vulnerable populations and ecosystems," he added.
Avian influenza detected in polar bears and studying the consequences of this fact
The governor of Svalbard said separately that the presence of the virus in the brain samples of the two animals "is consistent with the hypothesis that it was most likely the cause" of their deaths.

In 2023, a dead walrus from bird flu had already been found in Svalbard, and in the same year, the virus was also detected in a dead polar bear in Alaska.
Between January 2025 and March 2026, 140 million animals died or were slaughtered due to bird fl

u in nearly 70 countries, according to the World Organisation for Animal Health (OIE).
This is much lower than the peak recorded in 2021-2022, but the virus has since spread widely among non-avian species, increasing the risk of transmission to humans.
On a global scale, animal mortality due to this health crisis has been in the tens of millions in recent mon

ths. Although the total number of poultry casualties has decreased compared to previous crises, the scientific community is very concerned about the increasing adaptability of the pathogen in warm-blooded or

ganisms.
This constant mutation of avian influenza and the shift to new hosts not only threatens the ec

logical stability of remote nature reserves. The fact that they detect avian influenza in polar bears increases the danger of possible community transmission in humans.
The entry Avian Influenza Detected in Arctic Polar Bears was first

published on ECOticias.com.""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-23"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:52:33.509626+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.especes-menacees.fr/la-grippe-aviaire-detectee-chez-un-ours-polaire-dans-larctique/"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_la_vaccinazione_per_laviaria a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:la-vaccinazione-per-laviaria" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "e6b2dc44b02eb90b47e28548d6b4bf6840ef9e01357b51d884fb80416520034b" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Vaccination for avian flu" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Vaccination for avian flu

Vaccination for avian flu

Since May 2026, the Ministry of Health has launched a pilot vaccination project against highly pathogenic avian influenza, in collaboration with the Veneto and Lombardy regions, on a limited number of farms in the provinces of Verona and Mantua, a project concerning turkeys for meat and laying hens.

Calls to boycott companies participating in this pilot project have begun to appear on social media, indicating AIA as the only brand currently to be boycotted.

But the Ministry's managerial device identifies exactly 5 farms involved: 3 of broiler turkeys in the province of Verona and 2 of laying hens in the province of Mantua.

AIA does not know, nor does it emerge from any official source, that it is the only company to take part.

As reported by Telenuovo's Veronese TG, from 2020 to the beginning of 2026 there were 477 outbreaks of highly pathogenic avian influenza in Italian farms.

Numbers that have pushed towards overcoming emergency management based on culling, focusing on prevention and biosecurity, as also highlighted by the Istituto Zooprofilattico Sperimentale delle Venezie.

Those who push to boycott a single operator by explicitly naming him, while remaining silent about all the other participants in the same project, are at least exposing themselves to a reflection on the issue of unfair competition.

But it is not unfair competition that we want to talk about today, but about vaccines and avian flu.

The very first thing to say is that the messages calling for a boycott of AIA are pure misinformation, because we are talking about an mRNA vaccine, but the management device of the Ministry of Health that gives authorization to this vaccination test phase clearly states which vaccine can be used in the five farms, and it is not mRNA, but:
Beef turkeys
a) First vaccination: recombinant vaccine authorised for turkey with turkey herpesvirus (HVT) vector expressing the hemagglutinin H5 gene, administered in a hatchery on the first day of life.

(b) Second vaccination (booster): Inactivated vaccine authorised for turkey with subunits for H5, containing only the key protein of the virus (haemagglutinin, HA) and not the whole virus, administered at 30 to 36 days of age.

Pullets
a) First vaccination: recombinant vaccine authorised for chicken with HVT vector expressing hemagglutinin H5, administered in a hatchery on the first day of life.

(b) Second vaccination (booster): Inactivated H5 subunit vaccine authorised for chicken, containing only the key protein of the virus (haemagglutinin, HA) and not the whole virus, administered between 10 and 12 weeks of age.

The recombinant vaccine
It is a technology in use in veterinary medicine since the nineties, so if you worry today it is definitely late.

But to fully clarify let's try to understand what we are talking about.

This type of vaccine works like this: you take a virus that is already known and harmless to humans – in this case it is the turkey herpesvirus, which has been used for decades as a vaccine against Marek's disease – and insert the gene that codes for hemagglutinin H5, the surface protein of the avian flu virus.

The vector enters the animal's cells and produces that protein, training the immune system to recognize it.

No live influenza viruses are inoculated, no mRNA, and no modification to the animal's DNA occurs.

All very simple, and the booster of the second vaccination is even simpler since it is an inactivated vaccine that contains only the purified protein, without any genetic material.

Those who talk about "chicken mRNA" vaccination either don't know what they're talking about or are riding on misinformation to stimulate the indignation of an easily suggestible public.

As we have been saying for some time, fear is very useful when trying to influence public opinion.

Wrapping up
If I were in the Ministry of Health, I would immediately trigger complaints for procured alarm, as well as for possible damage to the companies mentioned.

But -'m just a fact checker.

----------- at Butac Punto IT
If you liked the article, support us on Patreon or PayPal!

Even the cost of a coffee can be enough!

Another way to support us is to buy one of the recommended books on our Amazon page, you can find it here.

BUTAC is also waiting for you on Telegram with the channel with all the updates.

Header image by Collab Media on Unsplash""" ;
    ts:sourcePublishedDate "2026-05-22"^^xsd:date ;
    ts:sourcePublisher "PADI-web" ;
    ts:sourceRetrievedAt "2026-05-28T19:53:46.028350+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    ts:sourceURL "https://www.butac.it/la-vaccinazione-per-laviaria/"^^xsd:anyURI .

tsd:news_padi_web_lutte_contre_la_grippe_aviaire_un_projet_pilote_au_zoo_de_la_palmyre_en_charente_maritime_1779718267 a ts:NewsReport,
