    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "WHO: construction helmets, AI and fake bird flu, what these former world leaders are organizing in Africa" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# WHO: construction helmets, AI and fake bird flu, what these former world leaders are organizing in Africa

WHO:

onstruction helmets, AI and fake bird flu, what these former world leaders are organizing in Africa

At the WHO emergency centre near
Nairobi, former heads of state in hard hats re-enact a
avian influenza pandemic in Chad. Behind this piloted scenario

hrough AI, finances, North-South inequalities and future treaties are at stake
pandemics.

At the World Healt

h Organization's Emergency Centre
Outside Nairobi, a dozen chefs
are leaning over a map of Chad. Construction helmets on
head, these members of The Eld

rs follow, on
AI-driven displays, the progression of a
Fictional outbreak of avian influenza.

Officially, this is a simulation exercise for
testing the preparedness of African countries for the next crisis.
But behind this fake pandemic lies a concrete question
: How does a poor state enforce the Regulations
international health policy, which requires reporting to the WHO
Any serious event in 24 hours, without ruining its economy?
A fake bird flu in Chad to test the
Global reflexes
The scenario presented to the Elders begins in eastern Chad, where
of caregivers report several deaths due to insufficiency
possibly related to a new influenza variant
avian. Samples must be sent abroad, but
the government is reluctant to alert the WHO, fearing stigma and
economic sanctions. -------

------- believes that there is a need for
Incentives for governments to "do the right thing"
thing".
In a second step, Chad ended up notifying the

HO, but
two weeks late: cases are already appearing in the
northern Cameroon and floods cut off roads,

blocking
sending samples to an international laboratory.
The exercise comes as an Ebola outbreak in Uganda and Uganda
Democratic Republic of the Congo has already caused at least 139
dead.
The Elders, ------------ and Alumni Diplomacy
Leaders
Created i

n 2007 by --------------, the group The
Elders brings together past presidents, leaders and
Nobel laureates who are determined to put

their experience at the service of
global crises. In Nairobi, ----- ---------------, former president
of Liberia, recalls that "Most of the time, it is not a
lack of political will as much as a failure of capacity
systemic". --------------------- s

ys he wants "a complete picture"
by bringing together climate and health experts.
This diplomacy of the elders is also illustrated by ------------.
In 2009, the former British Prime Min

ster chaired the summit
London G20, which has mobilised $1,100 billion to
avoid a new Great Depression.

Since 2021, it has been
WHO Ambassador for Global Health Financin

g,
Africa region recorded 146 disease outbreaks
in one year.
Between AI, pandemic treaty and mistrust
North-South
Before launching the role-playing game, the Elders follo

ed a
WHO presentation on how the organization is helping
African countries to deal with emergencies, and then on a new
AI-enabled system. According to the WHO, these simulat

ion exercises
are used to test plans, chains of c

ommand and coordination,
as a fire drill, even if they are sometimes caricatured
like a fake pandemic.
Around the table, participants know that the treaty
pandemic agreement promised in 2021 has not been final

zed,
after the vaccine inequity of Covid-19 in Africa. The surgeon
Congolese ------------- sums up: "We must work together
because we never know where it will happen." For the
WHO Regional Directo

r

, --------------, "You have seen what
we are fighting here," he said to the Elders. Epidemics will continue
; How we deal with them, that's the problem.\"""" ;
