tsd:news_padi_web_ouverture_du_marche_chinois_pour_les_pommes_belges a ts:NewsReport,
        ts:SourceDocument ;
    ts:referenceId "source_document:padi_web:ouverture-du-marche-chinois-pour-les-pommes-belges" ;
    ts:sourceContentHash "76ff2b3561b4ba27fd0e90eb8c00afba7632c4d4b980ba66534f799d7d3fe054" ;
    ts:sourceDocumentTitle "Opening of the Chinese market for Belgian apples: David Clarinval announces a historic agreement" ;
    ts:sourceFullText """# Opening of the Chinese market for Belgian apples: David Clarinval announces a historic agreement

Opening of the Chinese market for Belgian apples: David Clarinval announces a historic agreement

The working visit of the Federal Agency for the Safety of the Food Chain (FASFC) to China has literally borne fruit. After several year

of negotiations, the protocol "Protocol of phytosanitary re

uirements for export of f

esh apples from Belgium to China" was signed

by the FASFC with

he General Administration of Customs of China (GACC). This protocol defines the phy

osanitary conditions that Belgian apples must meet in order to be exported to China. The first exports are expected in the next growin

season at the earliest.
The FASFC visited China this week. On the one hand, China offers impo

rtant export opportunities for our Belgian c

mpanies and, on the other hand, the FASFC ensures that Chinese products imported into Belgium meet our strict requirements for food safety, animal health and plant health.
The signing of the protocol on the export of Belgian apples is a concrete result of this visit. It is now up to the fr

uit sector to comply with Chinese requirements so that apples can be marketed in China as early as the next

growing season. This protocol marks the official conclusion of the intensive negotiations between the FASFC and the GACC, which began in 2019 at the request of the Belgian fruit

ector.
David Clarinval, Minister of Agriculture:
"This historic agreement is great news for our farmers and our fruit sector. China is a huge market, and I

have been working with my administration for years to create concrete opportunities there. I congratulate the FASFC for the work accomplished and

I encourage the sector to prepare now to seize this opportunity. »
Christine Romeyns, Managing Director of the FASFC:
«
The signing o

this protocol is an important and long-awaited step for our fruit sector. It is the result of several years of patient work and d

alogue with our Chinese partners. It opens up concrete prospects for our producers, while reminding us that this opportunity comes with high standards
: Orcha

ds will need to be registered before exports can begin. Through this progress, we are preparing for s

stainable and credible access to this strategic market.
»
Image
* The protocol was signed by the FASFC's Managing Director, Christine Romeyns, and the Minister of the GACC
- General Administration of Customs of China

, Ms. Meijun Sun.
About the FASFC
For 25 years, the Federal Agency for the Safety of the Food Chain (FASFC) has been monitoring the entire food chain, from producer to

consumer. Around 1,400 employees carry out

more than 107,000 inspections in food companies

(farms, manufact

u

rers, slaughterhouse

s, shops, restaurants, etc.) every year and take and analyse around

67,000 product samples in the food chain. The Agency is also responsible for animal and pl

nt health controls and plays an important role in the import and export of food, animals and plants to and from other countries.
Press contact:
Aline Van den Broeck - Spokesperson
TEL: +32 497 59 24 69
E-mail:
aline.VandenBroeck@afsca.be""" ;
